So I'll pass it over to Nate.

00:03:09.010 --> 00:03:10.740
Hello, I'm Nate.

00:03:10.770 --> 00:03:15.120
I work on open sourced for most of my life.

00:03:15.150 --> 00:03:17.880
And recently I've become really enamored with AppProt

00:03:17.880 --> 00:03:18.040
on.

00:03:18.070 --> 00:03:19.890
So I'm working on, like, some SDKs for

00:03:19.890 --> 00:03:20.640
AppProton.

00:03:20.670 --> 00:03:24.650
And then recently a music app, which has sort of brought

00:03:24.650 --> 00:03:28.680
me into this problem of, like, what ways can artists

00:03:28.680 --> 00:03:32.500
, like, express how their content should be used.

00:03:32.530 --> 00:03:36.100
As Joe mentioned, like, how do you retain ownership of

00:03:36.100 --> 00:03:40.520
the content that you create without being subject to random things?

00:03:40.550 --> 00:03:43.970
So, yeah, I just think it's really exciting to

00:03:43.970 --> 00:03:48.470
sort of break open the problem that you get when you reverse

00:03:48.470 --> 00:03:50.740
the Faustian bargain that sort of she was referring to

00:03:50.740 --> 00:03:51.860
in the previous talk.

00:03:51.890 --> 00:03:53.320
So I'm excited to get into it.

00:03:53.470 --> 00:03:56.340
Awesome.

00:03:56.370 --> 00:03:57.000
Yeah.

00:03:57.710 --> 00:04:00.860
I guess everyone, the reason why everyone's here, everyone

00:04:00.860 --> 00:04:04.540
understands the issues with current social and the kind of power dynamics

00:04:04.540 --> 00:04:07.460
that are there, especially with content creators.

00:04:07.490 --> 00:04:10.830
Even looking at, you know, the creators, we're

00:04:10.830 --> 00:04:15.040
looking at catering to the most of their revenue sources that

00:04:15.040 --> 00:04:16.950
are not actually through the platforms they operate on.

00:04:17.130 --> 00:04:20.750
You know, the TikTok, Instagram, revenue sharing programs is

00:04:20.750 --> 00:04:23.620
actually a very, very small fraction of their revenue source.

00:04:23.650 --> 00:04:26.410
And it tends to be these kind of third-party brand

00:04:26.410 --> 00:04:29.800
sponsorships and things like that that make up, you know

00:04:29.870 --> 00:04:32.090
, the large portion.

00:04:33.710 --> 00:04:37.420
Yeah, Josh, you posted a really good leaflet recently

00:04:37.470 --> 00:04:41.930
about kind of redistribution, the redistribution of attention and

00:04:42.910 --> 00:04:46.200
especially with algorithms and feeds.

00:04:46.330 --> 00:04:48.260
So, yeah, I'd love to, if you could

00:04:48.760 --> 00:04:51.750
share your thoughts more on like how that can impact the creator

00:04:51.750 --> 00:04:53.940
economy specifically in the context of AppRoto.

00:04:53.950 --> 00:04:55.580
Sure.

00:04:55.610 --> 00:04:56.600
We'll do a quick survey.

00:04:56.630 --> 00:04:59.040
How many people post on social media?

00:04:59.070 --> 00:04:59.820
Put your hand up.

00:04:59.830 --> 00:05:01.780
All right.

00:05:01.970 --> 00:05:03.130
Everyone, hands down.

00:05:03.170 --> 00:05:07.700
Who makes meaningful income from their posts?

00:05:07.810 --> 00:05:08.540
Hands up.

00:05:08.570 --> 00:05:11.040
I see one hand in the room.

00:05:11.070 --> 00:05:11.560
Congrats.

00:05:13.630 --> 00:05:18.880
The reality is users and publishers are the stakeholders in these social

00:05:18.890 --> 00:05:21.380
networks that create value.

00:05:21.410 --> 00:05:24.580
But they're not the ones that capture the value.

00:05:24.610 --> 00:05:27.610
And this is because the platform at the end of the day

00:05:27.610 --> 00:05:30.160
is the entity that owns distribution.

00:05:30.190 --> 00:05:31.580
They own what...

00:05:31.610 --> 00:05:36.650
They're the ones who control what content users see and in

00:05:36.870 --> 00:05:37.980
what order.

00:05:39.070 --> 00:05:41.110
And they also control the interface.

00:05:41.370 --> 00:05:44.160
So, the screen real estate that users see.

00:05:44.190 --> 00:05:48.480
And these are really the two things that enable the platform to

00:05:48.480 --> 00:05:52.760
capture a meaningful majority of value on these platforms.

00:05:52.810 --> 00:05:58.350
And as the entity that captures the meaningful amount of value on

00:05:58.350 --> 00:06:03.140
these networks, the platform is also the arbiter of value

00:06:03.140 --> 00:06:03.480
.

00:06:04.090 --> 00:06:08.530
It is the entity that decides how that value gets allocated across

00:06:08.530 --> 00:06:14.110
the various stakeholders in its social network ecosystem.

00:06:14.450 --> 00:06:17.920
And ultimately, these platforms serve not users.

00:06:17.950 --> 00:06:19.170
They don't serve publishers.

00:06:19.210 --> 00:06:22.160
They serve shareholders at the end of the day.

00:06:22.190 --> 00:06:26.560
And so, there's really little to structurally no incentive

00:06:26.560 --> 00:06:31.200
for these platforms to share back revenue to creators.

00:06:31.230 --> 00:06:35.310
There are some of these creator monetization programs that exist where

00:06:35.310 --> 00:06:39.670
maybe a small fraction of advertising revenue is passed back to users

00:06:39.680 --> 00:06:40.490
and publishers.

00:06:40.530 --> 00:06:44.690
But they're prohibitively high thresholds to participating in

00:06:44.690 --> 00:06:46.040
these programs.

00:06:46.070 --> 00:06:49.430
And so, one of the core affordances that I mentioned

00:06:49.480 --> 00:06:52.100
of AppProto in my intro was this decoupling

00:06:52.200 --> 00:06:55.230
of data from application presentation.

00:06:56.130 --> 00:07:00.030
So, everyone's data lives in their own personal PDFs

00:07:00.030 --> 00:07:05.790
and applications tap into each user's respective PDFs and create

00:07:05.800 --> 00:07:10.640
an application view by tapping into this data.

00:07:11.370 --> 00:07:15.570
And so, one of the things that happens as a by

00:07:15.570 --> 00:07:20.470
product of this affordance is users in AppProto are

00:07:20.490 --> 00:07:26.480
able to create their own custom feeds and algorithms that live outside

00:07:26.480 --> 00:07:28.650
of the platform's control.

00:07:28.690 --> 00:07:31.940
And the algorithm at the end of the day is the thing

00:07:31.940 --> 00:07:37.260
that decides distribution, that decides who sees what content and in

00:07:37.280 --> 00:07:38.500
what order.

00:07:39.230 --> 00:07:43.280
And so, I'm hopeful that in this evolution of social

00:07:43.280 --> 00:07:48.390
platforms adopting AppProto and decoupling data from platforms

00:07:48.420 --> 00:07:52.510
themselves, we'll actually be able to live in a world

00:07:52.510 --> 00:07:58.160
of user-controlled algorithms versus platform-controlled algorithms.

00:07:58.190 --> 00:08:02.370
And that gives a lot more agency to the user and the

00:08:02.370 --> 00:08:06.190
creator as, well, number one, they get to take

00:08:06.190 --> 00:08:11.130
back control of distribution, which enables them to control what their

00:08:11.170 --> 00:08:12.500
audience sees.

00:08:12.630 --> 00:08:15.840
Today, if you're a user or publisher and you're

00:08:15.840 --> 00:08:20.090
broadcasting out into the social abyss, you have no control

00:08:20.220 --> 00:08:23.960
over what content your audience sees and in what order.

00:08:24.990 --> 00:08:27.200
And so, this is a really bad sort of trade-

00:08:27.400 --> 00:08:29.040
off for users and publishers.

00:08:29.070 --> 00:08:34.950
But if publishers are able to take back control of distribution through

00:08:34.950 --> 00:08:38.820
public feeds or through custom feeds and custom algorithms, not only

00:08:38.820 --> 00:08:42.320
do they take back distribution, but they also take back control

00:08:42.390 --> 00:08:43.030
of value.

00:08:43.170 --> 00:08:47.100
And now they become the arbiters of value in this ecosystem

00:08:47.100 --> 00:08:48.800
, not the platforms.

00:08:48.830 --> 00:08:53.280
And I'm hoping that with publishers and content creators becoming the

00:08:53.320 --> 00:08:57.080
arbiters of value in these ecosystems, now they're the

00:08:57.370 --> 00:09:01.940
ones that decide how that value gets allocated across the ecosystem.

00:09:02.510 --> 00:09:05.790
And I'm excited to see how this envelope of value could

00:09:05.790 --> 00:09:09.000
get distributed across various stakeholders.

00:09:09.030 --> 00:09:11.930
At the very extreme, you could imagine like Andra,

00:09:11.930 --> 00:09:16.010
for example, who runs the largest custom feeder algorithm on Blue

00:09:16.010 --> 00:09:18.880
Sky, a verified news feed that she built with Graze

00:09:18.960 --> 00:09:19.130
.

00:09:19.170 --> 00:09:23.080
She could embed advertising and sponsor posts within her feed, which

00:09:23.080 --> 00:09:26.250
she's already done, not at massive scale, and then

00:09:26.250 --> 00:09:29.850
redistribute all of that ad revenue that she generates to

00:09:29.850 --> 00:09:32.200
users or subscribers of her feed.

00:09:32.230 --> 00:09:35.830
And you could start to imagine how this envelope of value could

00:09:35.830 --> 00:09:40.280
get distributed across these various stakeholders that actually provide value to the

00:09:40.280 --> 00:09:44.300
feed or algorithm that creates these new incentives and new forms of

00:09:44.300 --> 00:09:45.940
economic coordination.

00:09:47.170 --> 00:09:55.800
So when you're talking about

00:09:55.810 --> 00:10:04.460
the redistribution of value

00:10:04.460 --> 00:10:13.170
to the creators, as a platform creator

00:10:13.170 --> 00:10:18.130
, as a venture capitalist, presumably this is actively against your

00:10:18.130 --> 00:10:20.410
core interests, right?

00:10:20.450 --> 00:10:22.750
Because in order for you to gain value from the thing you

00:10:22.890 --> 00:10:26.500
're creating, you need to control what people see because that

00:10:26.500 --> 00:10:30.400
gives your platform value that then you can extract for yourself,

00:10:30.400 --> 00:10:30.980
right?

00:10:31.010 --> 00:10:34.040
So how are you reconciling that?

00:10:34.070 --> 00:10:39.320
Like, are you planning on somehow building record deals with creators

00:10:39.330 --> 00:10:41.840
where they pay you for access to a platform?

00:10:41.870 --> 00:10:43.800
And if they are the ones who are the ones creating value

00:10:43.820 --> 00:10:48.480
, how does the platform or the venture capitalist add anything to

00:10:48.560 --> 00:10:50.850
that that makes it worth getting the share of the value in

00:10:50.850 --> 00:10:51.300
return?

00:10:51.470 --> 00:10:55.800
Great.

00:10:56.610 --> 00:10:57.400
Thank you for the question.

00:10:57.490 --> 00:10:59.420
It's obviously tough to be the bad guy.

00:11:01.070 --> 00:11:01.760
No, no, no.

00:11:01.760 --> 00:11:04.000
Look, I think the competitive vectors are going to change in

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:07.310
this space and the points of demand aggregation will change as

00:11:07.380 --> 00:11:07.840
well.

00:11:07.890 --> 00:11:11.140
Obviously, in this world, the creator has a lot more

00:11:11.140 --> 00:11:15.660
leverage as someone who controls their own distribution, owns their portable

00:11:15.830 --> 00:11:19.100
feed that they can take with them from one platform to another

00:11:19.220 --> 00:11:19.540
.

00:11:19.570 --> 00:11:23.600
I envision, again, it's still really early.

00:11:23.630 --> 00:11:25.910
It's still too early to say, but I envision,

00:11:26.040 --> 00:11:28.760
you know, companies like Graze, for example, will

00:11:28.780 --> 00:11:32.580
build, will almost become like the stripe for creators and build

00:11:32.580 --> 00:11:36.430
monetization tools for them that allow them to, you know

00:11:36.430 --> 00:11:39.180
, for example, Graze has already built an ad marketplace

00:11:39.210 --> 00:11:43.980
that allows for feed creators on Graze to embed advertising and

00:11:44.460 --> 00:11:46.800
sponsored ads within their feeds.

00:11:46.970 --> 00:11:50.210
And, you know, Graze will probably impose some sort

00:11:50.210 --> 00:11:52.500
of take rate on that transaction.

00:11:52.530 --> 00:11:55.760
And so, yeah, as more people use Graze,

00:11:55.760 --> 00:11:59.370
as more feed creators come on to Graze, as more

00:11:59.400 --> 00:12:02.970
attention concentrates in Graze feeds, you know, I

00:12:03.370 --> 00:12:06.640
expect Graze to, you know, potentially in the future

00:12:06.690 --> 00:12:10.240
, you know, participate in some of those economics where they

00:12:10.300 --> 00:12:16.320
're introducing advertisers to attention that takes place within these algorithms or

00:12:16.360 --> 00:12:19.000
feeds that creators produce.

00:12:19.150 --> 00:12:21.760
And I think the platforms will also play a role in this

00:12:21.760 --> 00:12:21.970
.

00:12:22.010 --> 00:12:24.340
Ultimately, if you create a feed or an algorithm, you

00:12:24.450 --> 00:12:27.380
still need distribution for your feeder algorithm.

00:12:27.430 --> 00:12:30.380
If you just create it and put it out into the world

00:12:30.380 --> 00:12:33.140
, there's not much value in that.

00:12:33.170 --> 00:12:34.500
You need people to view it.

00:12:34.530 --> 00:12:36.730
And, you know, Blue Sky has 40 million users.

00:12:36.790 --> 00:12:38.700
They provide distribution for feeds.

00:12:38.730 --> 00:12:40.710
They'll probably want a piece of the cut as well.

00:12:40.830 --> 00:12:45.440
Whenever they render an ad within one of these feeds, whenever

00:12:45.450 --> 00:12:47.790
a user looks at one of these feeds in the Blue Sky

00:12:47.790 --> 00:12:51.060
client and sees an ad, you know, that envelope of

00:12:51.060 --> 00:12:57.860
value will get split between the creator and the platform and probably

00:12:57.860 --> 00:13:02.420
Graze as well, who's like this monetization tool

00:13:02.420 --> 00:13:04.560
or infrastructure for creators.

00:13:05.030 --> 00:13:07.480
But, yeah, that's my response.

00:13:07.510 --> 00:13:11.220
Yeah, I mean, I'll just make a quick point

00:13:11.270 --> 00:13:12.340
and then we'll go to the question over there.

00:13:12.370 --> 00:13:15.320
From the perspective of someone that's, you know, building

00:13:15.320 --> 00:13:19.030
an app there, I think I echo Josh a lot there

00:13:19.030 --> 00:13:24.000
in that there's still the distribution surface.

00:13:24.030 --> 00:13:26.710
And I think it does flip the power dynamics, but there

00:13:26.710 --> 00:13:30.320
's still the requirement for the interface to get the creator's

00:13:30.690 --> 00:13:31.650
content to the audience.

00:13:31.690 --> 00:13:33.220
And there's costs involved with that.

00:13:33.250 --> 00:13:37.860
But I think that the competitive nature changes and the power dynamic

00:13:38.500 --> 00:13:39.060
changes.

00:13:39.090 --> 00:13:43.010
So, you know, the creator in this case has a

00:13:43.010 --> 00:13:47.020
lot more power and say and arguably more, much more bargaining

00:13:47.530 --> 00:13:49.340
power in that transaction.

00:13:49.370 --> 00:13:53.080
So, you know, the apps that exist, depending on

00:13:53.130 --> 00:13:56.760
what roles they play, you know, looking at protocols specifically

00:13:56.760 --> 00:13:57.920
, there's lots of different components.

00:13:57.950 --> 00:14:01.000
There's, they might host your PDS, which actually

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:02.940
has your content stored on it.

00:14:02.970 --> 00:14:04.980
It might, they might have the app view and they might

00:14:05.120 --> 00:14:06.100
be running the feed.

00:14:06.130 --> 00:14:07.290
They might be doing the moderation.

00:14:07.330 --> 00:14:10.120
They might have a full stack, in which case they deserve

00:14:10.120 --> 00:14:11.500
a larger bit of that pie.

00:14:11.530 --> 00:14:15.970
But ultimately, the creator has a lot more bargaining power and

00:14:16.010 --> 00:14:21.660
these kind of other components of the system fall further back into

00:14:21.680 --> 00:14:23.720
the, you know, into the background.

00:14:23.750 --> 00:14:27.050
And, you know, they basically play a role as a

00:14:27.050 --> 00:14:31.520
broadcaster or the rails for which a creator can access the

00:14:31.520 --> 00:14:32.340
audience.

00:14:32.370 --> 00:14:34.880
And the creator has the choice over which apps that they use

00:14:34.910 --> 00:14:36.760
as the surface to reach their audience.

00:14:37.330 --> 00:14:38.930
So, yeah, there was, I think there was a

00:14:38.930 --> 00:14:40.020
question over there.

00:14:40.170 --> 00:14:50.060
Hi.

00:14:50.650 --> 00:14:54.360
So, I actually use Graze to create feeds and I

00:14:54.370 --> 00:14:56.700
have one feed enabled for monetization.

00:14:56.730 --> 00:15:02.500
But what I've found in general with the feed creators with

00:15:02.500 --> 00:15:07.520
Graze is that most of us are trying to create these

00:15:07.520 --> 00:15:11.130
feeds, but we're not necessarily out there trying to market

00:15:11.130 --> 00:15:12.510
to get advertisers.

00:15:12.670 --> 00:15:15.400
Like, that's not our main skill set, if you

00:15:15.400 --> 00:15:16.000
will.

00:15:16.010 --> 00:15:21.340
Whereas the creators themselves who are trying to monetize their work

00:15:21.340 --> 00:15:23.140
are skilled at that.

00:15:23.170 --> 00:15:28.540
And so, I guess I wonder both what do you see

00:15:28.560 --> 00:15:33.210
as a way that we can actually get advertisers even wanting to

00:15:33.210 --> 00:15:35.840
be part of this system.

00:15:35.870 --> 00:15:36.620
Yeah.

00:15:36.650 --> 00:15:39.830
Like, how do you make that happen when you kind of

00:15:39.830 --> 00:15:45.530
have this weird distribution of creator versus more of a developer general

00:15:45.530 --> 00:15:47.170
interest person?

00:15:47.370 --> 00:15:47.820
Yeah.

00:15:47.850 --> 00:15:50.670
I mean, wherever there's eyeballs, there's going to

00:15:50.740 --> 00:15:51.440
be value.

00:15:51.470 --> 00:15:54.750
And right now, like, yeah, there's over 40

00:15:54.750 --> 00:15:57.960
million accounts on Blue Sky, but then there's even less

00:15:57.960 --> 00:15:59.880
if you look at the actual monthly active users.

00:15:59.910 --> 00:16:03.960
And there are already interests in advertisers, whether that's through

00:16:03.960 --> 00:16:06.850
Graze or people, you know, sponsored feeds or brands

00:16:06.850 --> 00:16:08.680
participating in the network.

00:16:08.730 --> 00:16:09.760
There's clear value there.

00:16:09.790 --> 00:16:10.380
There's eyeballs.

00:16:10.410 --> 00:16:10.980
There's attention.

00:16:11.470 --> 00:16:13.400
And where there's attention, there's money to be made

00:16:13.520 --> 00:16:15.620
, especially if we're looking at, you know, advertising

00:16:16.130 --> 00:16:16.400
models.

00:16:16.430 --> 00:16:17.970
But there's a lot of other models as well, I

00:16:17.970 --> 00:16:22.270
think, which come about when permission spaces become a thing on

00:16:22.270 --> 00:16:23.270
App Protocol.

00:16:23.450 --> 00:16:26.600
But, yeah, to answer your question, I think more

00:16:26.600 --> 00:16:29.460
that becomes a real thing.

00:16:29.570 --> 00:16:31.060
Sorry.

00:16:31.070 --> 00:16:33.100
Sorry about that.

00:16:35.230 --> 00:16:40.930
Yeah, I think I would like to ask Nate to pass

00:16:40.930 --> 00:16:42.540
it to you.

00:16:42.570 --> 00:16:45.130
I mean, we've talked a bit about more from this

00:16:45.130 --> 00:16:50.110
perspective of creators and ads and that being their kind of source

00:16:50.110 --> 00:16:50.900
of revenue.

00:16:50.930 --> 00:16:55.540
But for musicians and artists, it's a pretty different revenue

00:16:56.180 --> 00:16:56.320
source.

00:16:56.350 --> 00:16:59.690
And algorithms, especially today with, you know, apps like

00:16:59.690 --> 00:17:03.100
Spotify and Apple Music that have a real impact on how the

00:17:03.250 --> 00:17:06.010
music's created in the first place.

00:17:06.050 --> 00:17:09.760
How do you see kind of App Proto changing that landscape

00:17:09.810 --> 00:17:10.100
?

00:17:10.250 --> 00:17:13.180
Cool.

00:17:13.210 --> 00:17:16.200
So I'm really excited about, well, first of all

00:17:16.200 --> 00:17:18.300
, how many of you have heard of App Proto fans

00:17:18.500 --> 00:17:18.730
?

00:17:18.770 --> 00:17:20.660
Okay.

00:17:20.690 --> 00:17:21.780
A good chunk of you.

00:17:21.810 --> 00:17:24.010
For those of you who haven't, it's sort of

00:17:24.250 --> 00:17:26.940
like you show up, you hook up your bank, and

00:17:26.940 --> 00:17:29.740
then other people can show up and pay you five bucks,

00:17:29.870 --> 00:17:32.280
like coffee or something like this.

00:17:32.310 --> 00:17:36.540
And so what's exciting to me is that in my music

00:17:36.540 --> 00:17:41.090
app today, you can say when you upload a track or

00:17:41.090 --> 00:17:46.850
something, you can say only allow supporters to consume this track

00:17:46.850 --> 00:17:47.050
.

00:17:47.250 --> 00:17:49.610
And so I can just, as an app view or an

00:17:49.700 --> 00:17:54.900
application, just respect that stated support, which when permission data

00:17:54.900 --> 00:17:56.810
is a thing, that can be private as well.

00:17:58.270 --> 00:18:01.480
And so it's sort of more, it's just like

00:18:01.480 --> 00:18:07.440
Patreon style, like creators have relationships that they build grassroots with

00:18:07.440 --> 00:18:11.720
people that's sort of divorced from the classical conception of distribution

00:18:11.750 --> 00:18:15.200
or the advertising models, which is exciting to me personally.

00:18:16.590 --> 00:18:24.710
So I think the tricky part in my mind comes around when

00:18:24.710 --> 00:18:28.670
you ask a question like, if Spark is going to present

00:18:28.670 --> 00:18:32.950
a cameo of a song that appears on a music platform

00:18:32.990 --> 00:18:35.720
where the content is gated, how do you trickle

00:18:35.780 --> 00:18:38.860
the value back to the artist who owns it?

00:18:39.110 --> 00:18:44.100
How do you quantify the value that the artist is providing by

00:18:44.120 --> 00:18:45.920
allowing their content to show up downstream?

00:18:45.950 --> 00:18:51.300
And so I think that is where I want to press and

00:18:51.300 --> 00:18:54.120
try to figure out how do I do a handshake with

00:18:54.620 --> 00:18:57.960
Joe and say, how much is it worth to the artist

00:18:58.160 --> 00:19:00.640
for their content to appear there?

00:19:00.770 --> 00:19:03.740
And I think that's a very tricky problem.

00:19:03.770 --> 00:19:06.060
And I don't have any answers to that right now.

00:19:06.110 --> 00:19:08.720
But like, that is where I'm really interested in thinking

00:19:08.720 --> 00:19:08.720
.

00:19:08.730 --> 00:19:14.930
Because it does seem like the value of an impression depends entirely

00:19:14.950 --> 00:19:16.930
on like what the content is, first of all.

00:19:17.210 --> 00:19:18.840
And then second of all, the place where you see it

00:19:18.840 --> 00:19:18.840
.

00:19:18.870 --> 00:19:20.880
Like, because you can like, just hold up.

00:19:21.030 --> 00:19:23.040
Like, you can have your phone in front of you,

00:19:23.070 --> 00:19:24.290
but you can just not look at it.

00:19:24.330 --> 00:19:25.770
And it's like, the system might count that as an

00:19:25.770 --> 00:19:26.260
impression.

00:19:26.350 --> 00:19:29.310
So it's like, there's a lot of different human

00:19:29.310 --> 00:19:33.200
ways that I think we need to think about what the value

00:19:33.280 --> 00:19:39.790
of content distributing downstream is that I think is an important problem

00:19:39.820 --> 00:19:40.140
.

00:19:40.170 --> 00:19:44.050
But one thing I'm really excited about is that if an

00:19:44.340 --> 00:19:47.120
artist doesn't like the way that Joe and I do the

00:19:47.350 --> 00:19:49.720
handshake as far as like respecting the value of their content

00:19:49.720 --> 00:19:52.650
downstream, they can just take their content and go to a

00:19:53.310 --> 00:19:55.400
different app because of AppProto, which I think is

00:19:55.450 --> 00:19:56.020
really cool.

00:19:56.050 --> 00:19:58.420
And so maybe a different app does a better handshake in

00:19:58.420 --> 00:20:01.000
terms of respecting the value of their work downstream.

00:20:01.010 --> 00:20:02.760
But yeah.

00:20:02.770 --> 00:20:07.160
Yeah, I think that's a great point.

00:20:07.190 --> 00:20:11.510
I mean, I, you know, Spark and Player,

00:20:11.550 --> 00:20:13.410
we're going to interoperate one day, I promise

00:20:13.410 --> 00:20:13.710
you.

00:20:13.810 --> 00:20:16.580
We'll have, you know, you can add songs to

00:20:16.820 --> 00:20:19.380
Spark posts that are, you know, play a record.

00:20:19.410 --> 00:20:22.340
So an artist's song that they have on their PDS

00:20:22.370 --> 00:20:26.820
can start to propagate, interoperate across lots of different

00:20:26.870 --> 00:20:29.020
apps, not just Spark, but wherever there's music.

00:20:29.050 --> 00:20:33.470
And where these kind of value exchanges happen, I think there

00:20:33.470 --> 00:20:36.090
's, it's really important that there's some mechanism to

00:20:36.090 --> 00:20:37.260
share value there.

00:20:37.990 --> 00:20:40.980
I think right now we're starting to see like intra-

00:20:40.980 --> 00:20:44.010
app monetization models where, you know, Leaflet is

00:20:44.100 --> 00:20:46.920
launching Leaflet Pro and they have their monetization stream.

00:20:46.950 --> 00:20:48.170
You can subscribe to Leaflet.

00:20:49.250 --> 00:20:51.500
You know, you can have, there's other apps that

00:20:51.500 --> 00:20:54.000
are starting to do pro things as well or Graze has

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:55.880
their own advertising.

00:20:55.910 --> 00:20:58.240
But, you know, even if you're looking at a

00:20:58.350 --> 00:21:01.020
Graze feed, which taps into your question, a feed

00:21:01.030 --> 00:21:05.130
builder on Graze could have ads in their feed and Blue

00:21:05.190 --> 00:21:08.720
Sky that are actually taking on the majority of the costs and

00:21:08.720 --> 00:21:11.390
distributing that content is getting none of that.

00:21:11.930 --> 00:21:14.140
And sure, that works for now while they've got $

00:21:14.370 --> 00:21:16.480
100 million in the bank, but it's not going to

00:21:16.480 --> 00:21:18.020
be a sustainable ecosystem.

00:21:18.050 --> 00:21:21.960
So, I am a bit of a proponent for,

00:21:21.990 --> 00:21:24.220
and this came up in the previous talk, micropay

00:21:24.220 --> 00:21:27.760
ments there for the inter-app ecosystem.

00:21:27.790 --> 00:21:32.460
So, you know, for example, a player song being

00:21:32.460 --> 00:21:36.700
used on a sponsored post on Spark and a percentage of the

00:21:36.880 --> 00:21:40.980
revenue being made on that sponsored post automatically being distributed to the

00:21:41.050 --> 00:21:43.420
artist whose song is being used there.

00:21:43.450 --> 00:21:47.240
And that also could flow in the other direction where you have

00:21:47.550 --> 00:21:50.440
niche artists, which this exists on platforms today.

00:21:50.490 --> 00:21:53.010
There's these kind of shadow economies where up-and-

00:21:53.160 --> 00:21:58.260
coming musician will pay for a popular content creator to use their

00:21:58.260 --> 00:22:01.580
song on their post as a great way to get discovered.

00:22:01.610 --> 00:22:04.620
And we see TikTok has been such a great discovery mechanism for

00:22:04.620 --> 00:22:05.380
artists recently.

00:22:05.410 --> 00:22:08.350
And this doesn't just have to stay within the, you

00:22:08.350 --> 00:22:12.220
know, creators like artists and UGC creators.

00:22:12.250 --> 00:22:15.800
It can propagate across every other component of the ecosystem.

00:22:15.830 --> 00:22:19.540
PDS hosts, moderation services, app views, labelers

00:22:19.590 --> 00:22:20.660
, whatever.

00:22:20.770 --> 00:22:24.700
They can all become sustainable models that don't just rely on

00:22:25.090 --> 00:22:27.200
donations, but share in the value that's being created across

00:22:27.590 --> 00:22:28.260
the ecosystem.

00:22:28.330 --> 00:22:31.340
So, if anyone wants to chat micropayments on

00:22:31.340 --> 00:22:33.600
AppRoto, then please talk to me.

00:22:33.950 --> 00:22:35.640
So, yeah, I think we had a question.

