Yeah.

00:22:54.530 --> 00:22:55.500
My name is Hilke.

00:22:55.530 --> 00:22:59.780
I'm a musician myself and I run a music label.

00:22:59.810 --> 00:23:02.460
So, I know a bit how the music industry works.

00:23:02.470 --> 00:23:08.460
And, well, if you talk about monetization downstream for

00:23:08.490 --> 00:23:12.400
music that is posed on a...

00:23:12.430 --> 00:23:14.590
that is in a video, we have a system for that

00:23:14.870 --> 00:23:15.020
.

00:23:15.050 --> 00:23:15.900
It's called copyright.

00:23:15.930 --> 00:23:16.520
Yeah.

00:23:17.490 --> 00:23:20.120
And I think this has to play a role even if it

00:23:20.130 --> 00:23:24.020
looks much too complicated for technologists like many of us.

00:23:24.050 --> 00:23:28.000
But this is actually the system in place that the music industry

00:23:28.130 --> 00:23:29.400
and the big players use.

00:23:29.430 --> 00:23:34.390
And I think we need to find out with this protocol how

00:23:34.390 --> 00:23:39.060
we can map their data to the AppRoto data.

00:23:40.270 --> 00:23:43.510
And, yeah, I think that opportunity was missed in the

00:23:43.580 --> 00:23:46.620
first wave of Spotify and stuff.

00:23:46.650 --> 00:23:50.600
And then the whole mess that was made, then they had

00:23:50.600 --> 00:23:54.070
to buy out a bit of majors and that's how all

00:23:54.070 --> 00:23:57.190
the indie musicians and players got fucked.

00:23:57.270 --> 00:24:00.480
So, I think now we have the opportunity to do this

00:24:00.940 --> 00:24:02.220
mapping properly.

00:24:02.250 --> 00:24:07.560
And then the music industry, the labels, will get along

00:24:07.560 --> 00:24:11.860
, hopefully, with this ecosystem that we try to build.

00:24:11.890 --> 00:24:13.820
So, that is where...

00:24:14.310 --> 00:24:18.200
That's the reason why I made a proposal for Lexicon

00:24:18.230 --> 00:24:23.290
who does actually that, to translate the copyright system to App

00:24:23.290 --> 00:24:24.000
Roto.

00:24:24.010 --> 00:24:25.600
Yeah.

00:24:25.630 --> 00:24:28.860
I think looking at, like, TikTok as an example,

00:24:28.890 --> 00:24:34.210
you know, they have a pretty complete library of licensed music

00:24:34.220 --> 00:24:34.540
there.

00:24:34.570 --> 00:24:37.550
And they have deals with these record labels and they tend to

00:24:37.550 --> 00:24:40.400
pay, on average, 30 cents per song used on a

00:24:40.470 --> 00:24:41.100
post.

00:24:41.130 --> 00:24:46.500
And this is a very static dynamic and they are able to

00:24:46.510 --> 00:24:49.140
achieve that because they have, you know, economics of scale

00:24:49.300 --> 00:24:49.460
.

00:24:49.490 --> 00:24:51.600
They have a lot of bargaining power there and distribution.

00:24:51.630 --> 00:24:55.580
And I think looking at AtProtocol and music on

00:24:55.590 --> 00:24:58.010
AtProtocol, at least for now, there's

00:24:58.010 --> 00:25:00.930
kind of two angles, which is, one, there's

00:25:00.980 --> 00:25:03.690
that library completeness on one end, which requires a lot

00:25:03.690 --> 00:25:05.920
of capital, a lot of bargaining power that we don't

00:25:05.920 --> 00:25:06.240
have.

00:25:06.790 --> 00:25:09.340
And on the other end, it's starting from the indie

00:25:09.340 --> 00:25:14.130
artists, the creators at the other end that are starting from

00:25:14.130 --> 00:25:17.520
nothing and owning their content from the ground up.

00:25:17.590 --> 00:25:19.790
We can then, over time, build that and build that

00:25:20.190 --> 00:25:23.620
bargaining power and then get those kind of partnerships with real copyright

00:25:23.750 --> 00:25:27.470
and real respect for the laws that are necessary to protect artists

00:25:27.470 --> 00:25:27.660
.

00:25:29.730 --> 00:25:32.140
We don't have much time left, but I think there

00:25:32.270 --> 00:25:36.670
's a necessary topic to cover with the creator economy and that

00:25:36.670 --> 00:25:40.540
is AI, which is, you know, I think there

00:25:40.540 --> 00:25:45.210
's a lot of talk about gen AI affecting content creation and

00:25:46.250 --> 00:25:49.110
verification of what's real and what's not and that affecting

00:25:49.110 --> 00:25:49.840
the economies.

00:25:51.390 --> 00:25:52.950
Josh, as an investor, like, I would love to

00:25:52.980 --> 00:25:56.740
hear your thoughts on AI in the creator economy at large.

00:25:56.770 --> 00:26:01.130
Yeah, I think Natalie touched on this during the last talk

00:26:01.150 --> 00:26:01.840
pretty well.

00:26:01.870 --> 00:26:06.810
She spoke about how the covenant of the web is dead.

00:26:07.510 --> 00:26:09.920
Google scrapes websites in return.

00:26:09.950 --> 00:26:11.820
Websites get traffic.

00:26:11.850 --> 00:26:16.520
But we're evolving from a system of search engines to answer

00:26:17.030 --> 00:26:20.370
engines where, you know, it's nine, ten times

00:26:20.370 --> 00:26:23.380
harder to get traffic on Google now than it was 10 years

00:26:23.460 --> 00:26:23.780
ago.

00:26:23.810 --> 00:26:25.030
There's some stat.

00:26:25.070 --> 00:26:28.120
It's like 750 to 1,000 times harder to get

00:26:28.120 --> 00:26:33.120
traffic if you're a website from OpenAI and Anthropic

00:26:33.150 --> 00:26:34.700
and some of these model providers.

00:26:34.730 --> 00:26:37.320
So users aren't going to websites.

00:26:37.920 --> 00:26:43.180
They're just getting all the answers fed to them natively

00:26:43.710 --> 00:26:45.840
within an AI chat interface.

00:26:45.870 --> 00:26:49.760
And AI agents don't look at ads, right?

00:26:49.790 --> 00:26:51.960
And so, you know, for publishers, I'm thinking

00:26:51.980 --> 00:26:53.320
more news organizations.

00:26:53.370 --> 00:26:58.020
You know, the current business model of the web doesn't

00:26:58.040 --> 00:27:00.790
work with the way in which AI works.

00:27:00.850 --> 00:27:05.130
Because, you know, typically these news media organizations are monet

00:27:05.160 --> 00:27:11.130
izing traffic to their website and monetizing that attention and selling

00:27:11.130 --> 00:27:12.220
ads against it.

00:27:12.250 --> 00:27:14.880
And so, you know, obviously Cloudflare, you

00:27:14.880 --> 00:27:19.240
know, Microsoft are doing some interesting work around content data market

00:27:19.240 --> 00:27:19.900
places.

00:27:19.950 --> 00:27:23.960
Publishers create unique niche content.

00:27:23.990 --> 00:27:27.920
AI model providers need data to train their models.

00:27:28.770 --> 00:27:30.400
There was an interesting stat.

00:27:30.430 --> 00:27:34.710
So I think it was, I forget which AI model provider

00:27:34.710 --> 00:27:36.400
it was, so I won't say the name.

00:27:36.430 --> 00:27:39.340
But, you know, for the same amount of data,

00:27:39.370 --> 00:27:43.110
I believe Reddit got paid, it was something like, you

00:27:43.110 --> 00:27:46.910
know, five to seven X times more for their data.

00:27:46.970 --> 00:27:50.480
And the reason for that, relative to New York Times,

00:27:50.480 --> 00:27:50.820
sorry.

00:27:50.970 --> 00:27:53.940
And the reason for that is because the New York Times'

00:27:53.980 --> 00:27:57.180
